1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,600
Now let us look at a framework you will use throughout this entire series.

2
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:10,800
It is called the Accessibility in Practice model, and it has four areas.

3
00:00:10,800 --> 00:00:12,800
The first area is Awareness.

4
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:18,400
This means recognizing barriers and biases — including your own unconscious assumptions about disability.

5
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:22,000
Awareness is the starting point for every accessible interaction.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,000
The second area is Communication.

7
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,600
This means adapting how you share and receive information.

8
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:37,600
It could mean offering forms in large print, using plain language, providing a sign language interpreter, or simply asking someone how they prefer to communicate.

9
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:39,600
The third area is Environment.

10
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:42,800
This means shaping inclusive physical and digital spaces.

11
00:00:42,800 --> 00:00:47,600
Think about doorway widths, signage contrast, website navigation, and exam room layouts.

12
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:50,399
The environment either enables or prevents access.

13
00:00:50,399 --> 00:00:52,399
The fourth area is Response.

14
00:00:52,399 --> 00:00:57,199
This means acting with dignity and flexibility when someone needs something different.

15
00:00:57,199 --> 00:01:05,199
It is about how you react in the moment — with respect, without judgment, and with a willingness to adapt.

16
00:01:05,199 --> 00:01:07,199
These four areas work together.

17
00:01:07,199 --> 00:01:14,799
Throughout this series, each guide will explore how awareness, communication, environment, and response apply to a specific disability context.
